\begin_layout Standard
The GPR model and Godunov and Romenski's 1970s model of elastoplastic deformatio
n are very similar in structure.
 The differences lie in the physical interpretation of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, the appearance of algebraic source terms in the evolution equations for
 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

, and the inclusion of thermal conduction by the evolution of 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

.
 Whereas the earlier model described only solids, the new model seeks to
 describe fluids as well.
 In the former, 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 was viewed as describing the global deformation of the medium; it is now
 regarded as describing the local distortion of the material elements comprising
 the medium, containing information about their rotation and deformation.
 Unlike in previous continuum models, material elements have not only finite
 size, but also internal structure.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The strain dissipation time 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 of the HPR model is a continuous analogue of Frenkel's 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

particle settled life time
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "jacovfrenkel1947"

\end_inset

; the characteristic time taken for a particle to move by a distance of
 the same order of magnitude as the particle's size.
 Thus, 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}$
\end_inset

 characterizes the time taken for a material element to rearrange with its
 neighbors.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}=\infty$
\end_inset

 for solids and 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{1}=0$
\end_inset

 for inviscid fluids.
 It is in this way that the HPR model seeks to describe all three major
 phases of matter, as long as a continuum description is appropriate for
 the material at hand.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The evolution equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

 and its contribution to the energy of the system are derived from Romenski's
 model of hyperbolic heat transfer, originally proposed in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Malyshev1984,Romenski1988"

\end_inset

, and implemented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Romenski2007,Romenski2010"

\end_inset

.
 In this model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

 is effectively defined as the variable conjugate to the entropy flux, in
 the sense that the latter is the derivative of the specific internal energy
 with respect to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

.
 Romenski remarks that it is more convenient to evolve 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{J}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $E$
\end_inset

 than the heat flux or the entropy flux, and thus the equations take the
 form given here.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau_{2}$
\end_inset

 characterizes the speed of relaxation of the thermal impulse due to heat
 exchange between material elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The ADER-WENO Method
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-ADER-WENO-Method"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The ADER-WENO method was used in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dumbser2016a,Boscheri2016"

\end_inset

 to solve the GPR system.
 It produces arbitrarily high-order solutions to hyperbolic systems of PDEs
 and has been shown to be particularly effective for a wide range of systems
 (e.g.
 the classical Euler equations of gas dynamics, the special relativistic
 hydrodynamics and ideal magnetohydrodynamics equations, and the Baer-Nunziato
 model for compressible two-phase flow - see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Balsara2009,Zanotti2016"

\end_inset

).
 The first step in the process - the WENO method - will be used later in
 this study and is therefore discussed in detailed here.
 The remaining steps are described qualitatively, with references for further
 information given.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
WENO (Weighted Essentially Non-Oscillatory) methods are used to produce
 high order polynomial approximations to piece-wise constant data.
 Many variations exist.
 In this study, the method of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2013"

\end_inset

 is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $K,N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Take the set of grid points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\frac{i\cdot L}{K}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\ldots,K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=\frac{L}{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote cell 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x_{i},x_{i+1}\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Given cell-wise constant data 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

, an order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 polynomial reconstruction of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 will be performed.
 Define the scaled space variable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{i}=\frac{1}{\Delta x}\left(x-x_{i}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denoting the Gauss-Legendre abscissae on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{0},\ldots,\chi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

, define the nodal basis of order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

: the Lagrange interpolating polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{0},\ldots,\psi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the following property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{i}\left(\chi_{j}\right)=\delta_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is even, take the stencils:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
S_{1} & =\left\{ C_{i-\frac{N}{2}},\ldots,C_{i+\frac{N}{2}}\right\} \\
S_{2} & =\left\{ C_{i-N},\ldots,C_{i}\right\} \\
S_{3} & =\left\{ C_{i},\ldots,C_{i+N}\right\} 
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is odd, take the stencils:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
S_{1} & =\left\{ C_{i-\left\lfloor \frac{N}{2}\right\rfloor },\ldots,C_{i+\left\lceil \frac{N}{2}\right\rceil }\right\} \\
S_{2} & =\left\{ C_{i-\left\lceil \frac{N}{2}\right\rceil },\ldots,C_{i+\left\lfloor \frac{N}{2}\right\rfloor }\right\} \\
S_{3} & =\left\{ C_{i-N},\ldots,C_{i}\right\} \\
S_{4} & =\left\{ C_{i},\ldots,C_{i+N}\right\} 
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data is reconstructed on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{p}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}$
\end_inset

 are solutions to the following linear system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\Delta x}\int_{x_{k}}^{x_{k+1}}\sum_{p}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{k}\left(x\right)\right)\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}dx=u_{k}\qquad\forall C_{k}\in S_{j}\label{eq:WENOsystems}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 This can be written as 
\begin_inset Formula $M_{j}\boldsymbol{\hat{w}^{ij}}=\boldsymbol{u_{\left[j_{0}:j_{N}\right]}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ j_{0},\ldots,j_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 indexes the cells in 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 In this study reconstructions with 
\begin_inset Formula $N=2$
\end_inset

 are used.
 The matrices of these linear systems are given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:WENO-Matrices-for-N=2"

\end_inset

, along with their inverses, which are precomputed to accelerate the solution
 of these systems.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the oscillation indicator matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma_{mn}=\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N}\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{m}^{\left(\alpha\right)}\psi_{n}^{\left(\alpha\right)}d\chi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the oscillation indicator for each stencil:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
o_{j}=\Sigma_{mn}\hat{w}_{m}^{ij}\hat{w}_{n}^{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full reconstruction in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}\left(x\right)=\sum_{p}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\bar{w}_{p}^{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{w}_{p}^{i}=\omega_{j}\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the weighted coefficient of the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th basis function, with weights:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{j}=\frac{\tilde{\omega}_{j}}{\sum_{k}\tilde{\omega}_{k}}\qquad\tilde{\omega}_{j}=\frac{\zeta_{j}}{\left(o_{j}+\varepsilon\right)^{r}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=8$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=10^{-14}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{j}=10^{5}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a central stencil, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a side stencil, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The reconstruction can be extended to two dimensions by taking:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\upsilon^{i}=\frac{1}{\Delta y}\left(y-y_{i}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and defining stencils in the y-axis in an analogous manner.
 The data in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 is then reconstructed using stencil 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{p,q}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\psi_{q}\left(\upsilon^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\tilde{w}_{pq}^{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the coefficients of the weighted 1D reconstruction are used as cell
 averages:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
M_{j}\boldsymbol{\tilde{w}_{p}^{ij}}=\boldsymbol{\bar{w}_{p}^{\left[j_{0}:j_{N}\right]}}\qquad\forall p\in\left\{ 0,\ldots,N\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The oscillation indicator is calculated for each 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 in the same manner as the 1D case.
 The reconstruction method is easily further extensible to three dimensions,
 now using the coefficients 
\begin_inset Formula $\bar{w}_{pq}$
\end_inset

 of the weighted 2D reconstruction as cell averages.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The next process in the ADER-WENO method is to perform a Continuous Galerkin
 or Discontinuous Galerkin spatio-temporal polynomial reconstruction of
 the data in each cell, using the WENO reconstruction as initial data at
 the start of the time step (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Balsara2009"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dumbser2008"

\end_inset

 respectively for implementations of these two variations).
 The order of this reconstruction in time is usually taken to be the same
 as the spatial order, and the same basis polynomials are used.
 The process involves finding the root of a non-linear system, and this
 process is guaranteed to converge in exact arithmetic for certain classes
 of PDEs (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Jackson2017"

\end_inset

).
 This root finding can be computationally expensive relative to the WENO
 reconstruction, especially if the source terms of the PDE system are stiff.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The final step in the ADER-WENO method is to perform a finite volume update
 of the data in each cell, using the boundary-extrapolated values of the
 cell-local Galerkin reconstructions to calculate the flux terms, and the
 interior values of the Galerkin reconstructions to calculate the interior
 volume integrals.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

 for more details.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
An Alternative Numerical Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DensityEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MomentumEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DistortionEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ThermalEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EnergyEquation"

\end_inset

 can be written in the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:PDESystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

, a viable way to solve inhomogeneous systems of PDEs is to employ an operator
 splitting.
 That is, the following subsystems are solved:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q} & =\boldsymbol{0}\label{eq:HomogeneousSubsystem}\\
\frac{d\boldsymbol{Q}}{dt} & =\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:ODESubsystem}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advantage of this approach is that specialized solvers can be employed
 to compute the results of the different subsystems.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\delta t},S^{\delta t}$
\end_inset

 be the operators that take data 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t+\delta t\right)$
\end_inset

 under systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ODESubsystem"

\end_inset

 respectively.
 A second-order scheme (in time) for solving the full set of PDEs over time
 step 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

 is obtained by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}$
\end_inset

 using a Strang splitting:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}=S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}H^{\Delta t}S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}\boldsymbol{Q_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the scheme proposed here, the homogeneous subsystem will be solved using
 a WENO reconstruction of the data, followed by a finite volume update,
 and the temporal ODEs will be solved with appropriate ODE solvers.
 This new scheme will be referred to here as 
\shape italic
the Split-WENO method
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Homogeneous System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A WENO reconstruction of the cell-averaged data is performed at the start
 of the time step (as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:The-ADER-WENO-Method"

\end_inset

).
 Focusing on a single cell 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\boldsymbol{w^{n}}_{p}\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor product of basis functions in each of the spatial dimensions.
 The flux in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\approx\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{p}\right)\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are stepped forwards half a time step using the update formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}-\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}}{\Delta t/2}+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}=\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}-\frac{\Delta t}{2\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}$
\end_inset

 is the node corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This evolution to the middle of the time step is similar to that used in
 the second-order MUSCL and SLIC schemes (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

) and, as with those schemes, it is integral to giving the method presented
 here its second-order accuracy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}-\Delta t_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}+\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\varoint_{\partial C}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right),\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)d\boldsymbol{s}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{-},Q^{+}}$
\end_inset

 are the interior and exterior extrapolated states at the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}}{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}+\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 be the normal to the boundary at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\in\partial C$
\end_inset

.
 For the GPR model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{s}\right)\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonalizable matrix with decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\hat{R}\hat{\Lambda}\hat{R}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 are the right eigenvectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
 Define also 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}=\boldsymbol{F}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\boldsymbol{B}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions, the interface terms arising in the FV formula
 have the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}},\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)+\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 is chosen to either correspond to a Rusanov/Lax-Friedrichs flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\max\left(\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)\right|,\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right|\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or a simplified Osher–Solomon flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dumbser2011a,Dumbser2011b"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\int_{0}^{1}\left|\hat{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)\right|dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\hat{M}\right|=\hat{R}\left|\hat{\Lambda}\right|\hat{R}^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

 takes the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{B}=\int_{0}^{1}\hat{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the Osher-Solomon flux would often produce slightly less
 diffusive results, but that it was more computationally expensive, and
 also had a greater tendency to introduce numerical artefacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}},\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}$
\end_inset

 are calculated using an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

-point Gauss-Legendre quadrature, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Temporal ODEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\rho}{dt}=0$
\end_inset

 over the ODE time step, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 entails solving the following systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{dA_{ij}}{dt} & =\frac{-3}{\tau_{1}}\left|A\right|^{\frac{5}{3}}A\dev\left(G\right)\label{eq:DistortionODE}\\
\frac{dJ_{i}}{dt} & =-\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\frac{T\rho_{0}}{T_{0}\rho}J_{i}\label{eq:ThermalODE}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These systems can be solved concurrently with a stiff ODE solver.
 The Jacobians of these two systems to be used in an ODE solver are given
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Jacobian-of-Distortion-ODEs"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Jacobian-of-Thermal-Impulse-ODEs"

\end_inset

.
 However, these systems can also be solved separately, using the analytical
 results presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:GPR-Specific-Performance-Improvements"

\end_inset

, under specific assumptions.
 The second-order Strang splitting is then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}=D^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}T^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}H^{\Delta t}T^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}D^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}\boldsymbol{Q_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $D^{\delta t},T^{\delta t}$
\end_inset

 are the operators solving the distortion and thermal impulse ODEs respectively,
 over timestep 
\begin_inset Formula $\delta t$
\end_inset

.
 This allows us to bypass the relatively computationally costly process
 of solving these systems numerically.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
GPR-Specific Performance Improvements
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:GPR-Specific-Performance-Improvements"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Thermal Impulse ODEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Thermal-Impulse-ODEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The EOS for the GPR model 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EOS"

\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
T & =\frac{E_{1}}{c_{v}}\\
 & =\frac{E-E_{2A}\left(A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)}{c_{v}}-\frac{1}{c_{v}}E_{2J}\left(\boldsymbol{J}\right)\nonumber \\
 & =c_{1}-c_{2}\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\right\Vert ^{2}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
c_{1} & =\frac{E-E_{2A}\left(A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)}{c_{v}}\\
c_{2} & =\frac{\alpha^{2}}{2c_{v}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Over the time period of the ODE 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ThermalODE"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{1},c_{2}>0$
\end_inset

 are constant.
 We have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dJ_{i}}{dt}=-\left(\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\frac{\rho_{0}}{T_{0}\rho}\right)J_{i}\left(c_{1}-c_{2}\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\right\Vert ^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\therefore\frac{d}{dt}\left(J_{i}^{2}\right)=J_{i}^{2}\left(-a+b\left(J_{1}^{2}+J_{2}^{2}+J_{3}^{2}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
a & =\frac{2\rho_{0}}{\tau_{2}T_{0}\rho c_{v}}\left(E-E_{2A}\left(A\right)-E_{3}\left(\boldsymbol{v}\right)\right)\\
b & =\frac{\rho_{0}\alpha^{2}}{\tau_{2}T_{0}\rho c_{v}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that this is a generalized Lotka-Volterra system in 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ J_{1}^{2},J_{2}^{2},J_{3}^{2}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 It has the following analytical solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{J}\left(t\right)=\boldsymbol{J}\left(0\right)\sqrt{\frac{1}{e^{at}-\frac{b}{a}\left(e^{at}-1\right)\left\Vert \boldsymbol{J}\left(0\right)\right\Vert ^{2}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The Distortion ODEs
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-Distortion-ODEs"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Reduced Distortion ODEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $k_{0}=\frac{3}{\tau_{1}}\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{5}{3}}>0$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 have singular value decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $U\Sigma V^{T}$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
G=\left(U\Sigma V^{T}\right)^{T}U\Sigma V^{T}=V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tr\left(G\right)=\tr\left(V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}\right)=\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}V^{T}V\right)=\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\therefore\frac{dA}{dt} & =-k_{0}U\Sigma V^{T}\left(V\Sigma^{2}V^{T}-\frac{\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)}{3}I\right)\\
 & =-k_{0}U\Sigma\left(\Sigma^{2}-\frac{\tr\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)}{3}\right)V^{T}\nonumber \\
 & =-k_{0}U\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)V^{T}\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It is a common result (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Giles2008"

\end_inset

) that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d\Sigma=U^{T}dAV
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{d\Sigma}{dt}=-k_{0}\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using a fast 
\begin_inset Formula $3\times3$
\end_inset

 SVD algorithm (such as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "McAdams2011"

\end_inset

), 
\begin_inset Formula $U,V,\Sigma$
\end_inset

 can be obtained, after which the following procedure is applied to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Sigma$
\end_inset

, giving 
\begin_inset Formula $A\left(t\right)=U\Sigma\left(t\right)V^{T}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote the singular values of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{1},a_{2},a_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 Then:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma\dev\left(\Sigma^{2}\right)=\left(\begin{array}{ccc}
a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right) & 0 & 0\\
0 & a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right) & 0\\
0 & 0 & a_{1}\left(a_{1}^{2}-\frac{a_{1}^{2}+a_{2}^{2}+a_{3}^{2}}{3}\right)
\end{array}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{\det\left(A\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}}=\frac{a_{i}^{2}}{\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{2}{3}}}$
\end_inset

 we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}=-3x_{i}\left(x_{i}-\bar{x}\right)\label{eq:StretchODESystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau=\frac{2}{\tau_{1}}\left(\frac{\rho}{\rho_{0}}\right)^{\frac{7}{3}}t$
\end_inset

.
 This ODE system travels along the surface 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi=\left\{ x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}>0,x_{1}x_{2}x_{3}=1\right\} $
\end_inset

 to the point 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{3}=1$
\end_inset

.
 This surface is symmetrical in the planes 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{2}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}=x_{3}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}=x_{3}$
\end_inset

.
 As such, given that the system is autonomous, the paths of evolution of
 the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 cannot cross the intersections of these planes with 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, any non-strict inequality of the form 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}\geq x_{j}\geq x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is maintained for the whole history of the system.
 By considering 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:StretchODESystem"

\end_inset

 it is clear that in this case 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 is monotone decreasing, 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{k}$
\end_inset

 is monotone increasing, and the time derivative of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}$
\end_inset

 may switch sign.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we have:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \begin{array}{c}
\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}=-x_{i}\left(2x_{i}-x_{j}-x_{k}\right)=-x_{i}\left(2x_{i}-x_{j}-\frac{c}{x_{i}x_{j}}\right)\\
\frac{dx_{j}}{d\tau}=-x_{j}\left(2x_{j}-x_{k}-x_{i}\right)=-x_{j}\left(2x_{j}-x_{i}-\frac{c}{x_{i}x_{j}}\right)
\end{array}\right.\label{eq:2odes}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus, an ODE solver can be used on these two equations to effectively solve
 the ODEs for all 9 components of 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

.
 Note that:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{dx_{j}}{dx_{i}}=\frac{x_{j}}{x_{i}}\frac{2x_{j}-x_{i}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}}{2x_{i}-x_{j}-\frac{1}{x_{i}x_{j}}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This has solution:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
x_{j}=\frac{c+\sqrt{c^{2}+4\left(1-c\right)x_{i}^{3}}}{2x_{i}^{2}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
c=-\frac{x_{i,0}\left(x_{i,0}x_{j,0}^{2}-1\right)}{x_{i,0}-x_{j,0}}\in\left(-\infty,0\right]
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the case that 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i,0}=x_{j,0}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=x_{j}$
\end_inset

 for all time.
 Thus, the ODE system for 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has been reduced to a single ODE, as 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{j}\left(x_{i}\right)$
\end_inset

 can be inserted into the RHS of the equation for 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{dx_{i}}{d\tau}$
\end_inset

.
 However, it is less computationally expensive to evolve the system presented
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:2odes"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

